## Vulnerability Report

**PDF Hyperlink URL Validation Bypass - Unsafe Intent Launch**

**Location**: `m365-decompiled/sources/com/microsoft/mspdf/v1.java`, lines ~133-173 (`onChanged()` default case)

**Vulnerability Description**:
When a user taps a hyperlink inside a PDF document, the native PDF library calls `MessageNotifier.notifyNavigateTo(url)`, which propagates through `v2.invoke(case 2)` → `h3.Q0.postValue(url)` → `v1.onChanged(url)`. The URL validation is severely insufficient.

**Vulnerable Code Pattern**:
```java
// v1.java, default case in onChanged()
String str = (String) obj; // URL from PDF link - attacker controlled
Locale locale = Locale.getDefault();
String lowerCase = str.toLowerCase(locale);
boolean zH1 = kotlin.text.t.h1(lowerCase, "file:", false);
// Only blocks file:// and ftp:// schemes
if (zH1 || kotlin.text.t.h1(lowerCase, "ftp:", false)) {
    // blocked
} else {
    if (Uri.parse(str) != null) {
        Intent intent = new Intent("android.intent.action.VIEW");
        intent.addFlags(268435456); // FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK
        intent.setData(Uri.parse(str).normalizeScheme());
        // Launched with no scheme allowlist
        e2Var2.startActivity(intent);
    }
}
```

**Data Flow**:
1. Attacker creates a malicious PDF with a hyperlink set to a dangerous URI
2. User opens the PDF in M365 Android
3. User taps the link
4. Native `libPdfControl.so` fires `notifyNavigateTo(url)` (via JNI callback to MessageNotifier.java)
5. URL flows to `v1.onChanged()` with only `file:` and `ftp:` blocked
6. `ACTION_VIEW` Intent is fired with the attacker-controlled URI

**Attack Vectors**:
- `intent://` URIs: Can trigger any exported Intent on the device, potentially launching privileged internal activities with attacker-controlled extras
- `market://` / `vnd.youtube://` / custom app scheme URIs: Can force arbitrary app-to-app communication
- `content://` URIs: May expose internal content providers  
- `javascript:` URIs: If resolved by a browser WebView
- `tel:`, `sms:`, `mailto:` URIs with pre-filled content: Social engineering / phishing via crafted PDFs
- Any custom URI scheme registered by apps installed on the device

**Insufficient Block List**:
Only `file:` and `ftp:` are blocked. A safe implementation would use an explicit allowlist (only `http:`, `https:`) or validate against a blocklist that includes `intent:`, `content:`, `javascript:`, `file:`, `ftp:`, etc.

**Impact**: Opening a malicious PDF can trigger arbitrary Android Intent dispatch, potentially launching privileged activities, bypassing app sandbox restrictions, or performing social engineering attacks. With `intent://` URIs, it may be possible to reach unexported or internal activities in other apps.

## Related Files

- `m365-decompiled/sources/com/microsoft/mspdf/v1.java`
- `m365-decompiled/sources/com/microsoft/mspdf/MessageNotifier.java`
- `m365-decompiled/sources/com/microsoft/mspdf/v2.java`
- `m365-decompiled/sources/com/microsoft/mspdf/h3.java`

