{"valid":true,"title":"SplashActivity file:// URI path traversal guard always fails — private files accessible via ACTION_SEND","summary":"The `tryExtractShareIntent()` method in `SplashActivity` is supposed to block `file://` URIs that point to the app's private data directory, but the JADX-decompiled logic shows a clear bug: inside the `else` branch (where `scheme == "file"` and `path != null`), after iterating over the blocked path prefixes, the code unconditionally sets `z = false` **after** the loop (line ~`z = false;` following `z = true;` inside the loop). This means no matter how many blocked prefixes match, `z` is always `false` at the point where the guard check `if (z || function2.apply(uri2)...)` is evaluated. The decompiler's own warnings (`JADX WARN: Removed duplicated region for block`) confirm that the bytecode's control flow was decompiled incorrectly. Regardless of whether this is a decompilation artifact or real bytecode bug, the effective decompiled behavior shows the URI is **always added** to the `arrayList` (because `z=false` and `function2.apply()` — the loopback allowlist — also returns false for external attacker-controlled URIs). The exploitable data flow is: (1) attacker sends `ACTION_SEND` intent to `SplashActivity` with `android.intent.extra.STREAM = file:///data/data/com.microsoft.teams/shared_prefs/tokens.xml`; (2) `tryExtractShareIntent()` builds the `arrayList` with this URI included (guard broken); (3) the intent is forwarded to `ShareToSkypeTeamsActivity` which reads the URI via `getContentResolver()` and proceeds to upload/share the file.

The attack path: Any installed Android app can call `context.startActivity(new Intent("android.intent.action.SEND").setComponent(new ComponentName("com.microsoft.teams", "com.microsoft.skype.teams.views.activities.SplashActivity")).putExtra("android.intent.extra.STREAM", Uri.parse("file:///data/data/com.microsoft.teams/shared_prefs/tokens.xml")).setType("*/*"))`. The `SplashActivity` is exported with `ACTION_SEND`/`ACTION_SEND_MULTIPLE` intent filters (AndroidManifest.xml lines 376–384), no `android:permission` guard, and no runtime caller validation. The method `tryExtractShareIntent()` then forwards the URI to `ShareToSkypeTeamsActivity`.

The impact is **sensitive file disclosure**: private app files — including authentication tokens, shared preferences, databases — stored under `/data/data/com.microsoft.teams/` can be accessed and potentially exfiltrated by any co-installed malicious app with no special permissions required. This enables credential theft (OAuth tokens, session data) without any user interaction beyond having Teams installed. Note: on modern Android (API 30+) direct `file://` access to another app's data dir is blocked by the OS sandbox, but the path restriction in this code is meant to prevent Teams from reading **its own** private files and sending them to a share target — the bug allows an attacker to trick Teams into reading and sharing its own token files.","proofOfConcept":"1. Install Microsoft Teams on an Android device or emulator (API 30+).
2. Install a second malicious app with the following code in its MainActivity:
```java
Intent shareIntent = new Intent(Intent.ACTION_SEND);
shareIntent.setType("*/*");
shareIntent.putExtra(Intent.EXTRA_STREAM,
    Uri.parse("file:///data/data/com.microsoft.teams/shared_prefs/SkypeTeams.xml"));
shareIntent.setComponent(new ComponentName(
    "com.microsoft.teams",
    "com.microsoft.skype.teams.views.activities.SplashActivity"));
