{"valid":true,"title":"Unsanitized JavaScript-to-Native Token Bridge Allows Arbitrary AAD Token Acquisition via StreamPlayerView WebView","summary":"## Vulnerability Overview

The `StreamPlayerView.JavaScriptInterface.getAuthToken(String str, String str2)` method, exposed via `@JavascriptInterface` to any JavaScript running in the WebView, accepts a **resource URL** (`str`) and a **claims challenge** (`str2`) with **no domain allowlist validation**. The resource string is sanitized only by appending `/.default` (via `MathUtils.getDefaultScopedResource()`), not by validating it against any permitted set of AAD resources. This means any JavaScript call to `NativeInterface.getAuthToken("https://management.azure.com", "")` will cause the app to acquire and return a bearer token for Azure Resource Manager to the calling JS.

## Attack Path

The WebView loads `tabIFrameHostUrl` from `activeConfiguration`, which defaults to `https://teams.microsoft.com/iframe-container.html` in `CommonConfiguration`. An attacker who can execute JavaScript in that page — via XSS on `teams.microsoft.com` — can call:
```javascript
window.NativeInterface.getAuthToken('https://management.azure.com', '')
window.NativeInterface.getAuthToken('https://graph.microsoft.com', '')
window.NativeInterface.getAuthToken('https://storage.azure.com', '')
```
