## Vulnerability Report

Nested App Authentication (NAA) Redirect URI Validation is Telemetry-Only - No Security Enforcement

In Microsoft Teams' Nested App Authentication (NAA) broker flow, the `nestedAppAcquireToken` function in `397462-92cb869a825fcf2f.js` (class `Ie`, method at the bottom of file) performs only a telemetry log when the `redirectUri` does not include the expected `brk-multihub://` scheme, with no enforcement blocking the request from proceeding:

```javascript
// In Ie.nestedAppAcquireToken (397462-92cb869a825fcf2f.js)
(!t.redirectUri || !t.redirectUri.includes("brk-multihub://")) && 
    i.addEventData(["invalidNestedAppRedirectUri:true", `nestedRedirectUri:${!!t.redirectUri}`]);
// Token acquisition proceeds regardless
const m = await p.acquireToken(t.target, g);
```

The MSAL layer in `msal-service-e0600589092a1518.js` (class `Msal2AuthenticationProvider`, function `_getAccessTokenRequest`) also only logs telemetry:
```javascript
e.addEventData([
    `nestedRedirectUri:${+!!l?.nestedRedirectUri}`,
    `nestedClientId:${+!!l?.nestedClientId}`, ...
]);
if (this._redirectUri && l?.nestedRedirectUri && l?.nestedClientId) {
    e.addEventData(["nestedAuthRequest:1"]);
    // Sets D.redirectUri = j (the nestedRedirectUri from the app!)
    // Sets D.extraQueryParameters with brk_client_id, brk_redirect_uri
    // D.storeInCache = {idToken: false, accessToken: false}
    D.redirectUri = j; // j = l.nestedRedirectUri from nested app
    ...
}
```

The `nestedRedirectUri` provided by the nested app (third-party tab) is used **directly** as the redirect URI in the MSAL token request (`D.redirectUri = j`) without validating it against any allowlist. Only a logging check (`invalidNestedAppRedirectUri:true`) fires when it does not start with `brk-multihub://`, but token acquisition proceeds regardless.

**Impact**: A malicious nested app hosted inside a Teams tab could supply an arbitrary `redirectUri` in its token request. The Teams broker would forward the URI to AAD and acquire tokens on behalf of the user using attacker-controlled redirect URIs, which could then be used in auth code phishing flows or to redirect tokens to an attacker-controlled endpoint.

