{"valid":false,"title":"AES/GCM IvParameterSpec Does Not Bypass Authentication Tag Verification on Android","summary":"The report claims that using `IvParameterSpec` instead of `GCMParameterSpec` when initializing an AES/GCM cipher on Android causes the GHASH authentication tag to be silently skipped, degrading the cipher to unauthenticated AES-CTR mode.

This claim is **technically incorrect for Android's Conscrypt JCA provider**, which is the default provider since Android API 10+ and mandatory from API 23+. The app targets `minSdkVersion=30`, meaning all supported devices use Conscrypt. Conscrypt accepts both `IvParameterSpec` and `GCMParameterSpec` for AES/GCM/NoPadding. When `IvParameterSpec` is used, Conscrypt simply applies the default 128-bit GCM authentication tag length — it does **not** skip tag verification. Any attempt to decrypt tampered ciphertext will throw `AEADBadTagException`, just as it would with `GCMParameterSpec`. The tag length does not silently reduce to 64 bits either; Conscrypt defaults to 128-bit tags.

Furthermore, the vulnerability's attack scenario requires physical access to the device, root access, or access to SharedPreferences — none of which is achievable by a remote attacker. The encryption key (`TOKEN_PREF_KEY`) is stored separately in `YammerSimpleData` SharedPreferences and is not exposed over any network interface. Even if one accepts the theoretical cryptographic weakness (which is not real in this context), exploiting the bit-flipping attack would require reading the encrypted SharedPreferences file AND writing a modified ciphertext back — both requiring local device compromise. There is no remote code path that exposes this data to an unauthenticated attacker.","proofOfConcept":"To independently verify that IvParameterSpec does NOT skip GCM auth tag verification on Android:

1. Write a simple Android test:
```java
Cipher cipher = Cipher.getInstance("AES/GCM/NoPadding");
byte[] key = new byte[32]; new SecureRandom().nextBytes(key);
byte[] iv = new byte[16]; new SecureRandom().nextBytes(iv);
SecretKey secretKey = new SecretKeySpec(key, "AES");

// Encrypt
cipher.init(Cipher.ENCRYPT_MODE, secretKey, new IvParameterSpec(iv));
byte[] ciphertext = cipher.doFinal("test token".getBytes());

// Tamper with ciphertext
ciphertext[0] ^= 0xFF;

// Decrypt - try with IvParameterSpec (the allegedly vulnerable path)
Cipher decCipher = Cipher.getInstance("AES/GCM/NoPadding");
decCipher.init(Cipher.DECRYPT_MODE, secretKey, new IvParameterSpec(iv));
try {
    decCipher.doFinal(ciphertext); // This WILL throw AEADBadTagException
    System.out.println("TAG BYPASSED - vulnerable");
} catch (AEADBadTagException e) {
    System.out.println("TAG ENFORCED - not vulnerable"); // This is what happens
}
```
2. Run on any Android device with API >= 23. The decryption WILL throw `AEADBadTagException`, confirming authentication is enforced.
3. The Conscrypt source code at `conscrypt/src/main/java/org/conscrypt/OpenSSLCipher.java` confirms `IvParameterSpec` is handled identically to `GCMParameterSpec` with a 128-bit default tag.
4. Even ignoring the above, any exploitation requires root/physical access to the device to read SharedPreferences — not remotely achievable.","severity":"low"}

