## Vulnerability Report

## Medium: ECS License Check Bypass via enableOverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck Flag

### Vulnerability Description
`QrCodeCreateGroupCopilotMeetingAction.getSupportedResult()` checks an ECS (Experimentation and Configuration Service) feature flag `enableOverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck` that bypasses the Group Copilot license requirement. If an attacker can influence ECS flag delivery (e.g., via MITM on an unverified ECS endpoint), they can force the license check bypass.

### Code Evidence (QrCodeCreateGroupCopilotMeetingAction.java)
```java
// In getSupportedResult():
INativeCoreExperimentationManager iNativeCoreExperimentationManager = this.experimentationManager;
if (!iNativeCoreExperimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsBoolean("enableOverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck") 
    && !this.userConfiguration.isGroupCopilotEnabled()) {
    listCreateListBuilder.add(QrCodeUnsupportedReason.GROUP_COPILOT_LICENSE_REQUIRED);
}

// In execute():
if (this.experimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsBoolean("enableOverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck")) {
    scenarioContextM.logStep("LiveNotes_OverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck");
}
```

### ECS Trust Chain Issue
ECS flags are fetched from Microsoft's experimentation service. If ECS requests lack certificate pinning (which creates a circular bootstrap dependency problem — you need ECS to get pinning config, but need pinning to securely fetch ECS), an adversary-in-the-middle on the network could inject `enableOverrideGroupCopilotLicenseCheck: true` and `enableQrCodeCreateGroupCopilotMeetingAction: true`, effectively enabling the Group Copilot meeting creation action for users without the required license.

### Additional ECS-Controlled Values in DcfSignInWebViewerViewModel
The following critical values are ECS-controlled and could be manipulated:
```java
this.loginUrl = experimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsString("dcfSignInLoginUrl", "https://login.microsoftonline.com/common/oauth2/deviceauth");
this.loginCompletedUrl = experimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsString("dcfSignInCompleted", "https://login.microsoftonline.com/appverify");
this.dcfCodeTextBoxId = experimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsString("dcfCodeTextBoxId", "otc");
this.loginPageSubmitFormId = experimentationManager.getEcsSettingAsString("dcfSignInPageSubmitFormId", "i5528");
```

If ECS is compromised/MITMed, an attacker can change the `loginUrl` to a phishing page and `loginCompletedUrl` to match it (triggering "success" immediately), turning the DCF sign-in WebView into a credential phishing mechanism that completes successfully from the app's perspective.

### Files Involved
- `QrCodeCreateGroupCopilotMeetingAction.java`
- `DcfSignInWebViewerViewModel.java` (ECS-controlled URLs and form field IDs)
- `ActivityDcfSignInBindingImpl.java` (loadUrl called with ECS-controlled URL)

